INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (955, 4647, 'Guy Cuthbert', 'guy.cuthbert@atheon.co.uk', '', '109.144.222.28', '2013-03-12 11:02:37', '2013-03-12 15:02:37', 'Big Data is certainly flavour of the year, but far too many businesses - retailer and consumer goods suppliers included - are leaping in without the requisite analytical skills. The primary check is to ask:\r\n\r\n"How effective are we at analysing our *small* data?"\r\n\r\nFor a great many businesses, including many multi-national household names, the answer is weak; analytics is poorly understood and a surprisingly large number of organisations who claim to apply analytics to their data simply report on it, and don\'t *analyse* it at all.\r\n\r\nWe need to see a grow in commercial analytics - a recent Harvard Business Review article (see http://hbr.org/2013/01/why-it-fumbles-analytics/ar/1) hits the nail on the head perfectly. Before any of us gets carried away with Big Data - and yes, it does offer tremendous opportunity through genuine insight - we need to get our houses in order, and establish effective, credible, actionable analytics.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.2; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.22 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/25.0.1364.152 Safari/537.22', '', 0, 0, 'N'); 
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (958, 4647, 'Joshua Roberts', 'joshua.roberts@getchee.com', 'http://www.getchee.com/', '1.160.243.134', '2013-03-12 22:07:11', '2013-03-13 02:07:11', 'Hi Guy,\r\n\r\nYou’re right; the HBR article about why IT fumbles analytics makes a ton of great points. Thanks for that.\r\n\r\nPurely storing and/or reporting on data is not sufficient to make real discoveries, beneficial decisions, and provide context for those ‘a-ha’ moments. The human factor must be brought back through analysts to make sense of it all and filter.\r\n\r\nBig Data has certainly turned into a buzzword in the last year or two. I know that when used in the right hands, by the right people, it can be used to make powerful discoveries and correlations.\r\n\r\n‘Small Data’, as you point out, should take more of a priority for many corporations that have really not taken advantage of the data they have sitting on their own corporate servers, email in-boxes, and employee’s heads.\r\n\r\nIt’s pretty amazing that a lot of information about how to better your offerings stares you in the face every day, but because it is not A. properly stored, and B. not properly filtered/analyzed, much of the valuable information goes unnoticed. Things like…\r\n\r\nWhat are our customers and competition telling us (directly or indirectly)? How are we using that information to better our offerings? This has little to do with the IT or systems in place to collect the information, but more to do with how to use/analyze the information (to your point).\r\nAny way you look at it, data (big or small), needs to be stored and organized, and then analyzed using the right questions and assumptions.\r\n\r\nWhile getchee focuses its attention on location-based data and the analysis of it to discover spatial relationships, I think there is much to learn from harnessing the ‘Small Data’ that every corporation has sitting around in various locations.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.22 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/25.0.1364.152 Safari/537.22', '', 955, 1, 'N'); 
INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (971, 4647, 'Guy Cuthbert', 'guy.cuthbert@atheon.co.uk', '', '213.249.153.16', '2013-03-13 09:09:23', '2013-03-13 13:09:23', 'Joshua\r\n\r\nYou\'re welcome - I enjoyed the original piece, and it\'s interesting to see what you\'re up to. I guess we\'re both keen to see people thinking about *genuine analytics* (rather than re-hashed reporting), and that\'s where the HBR article seems to resonate with us both :)\r\n\r\nRegards\r\n\r\nGuy', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.2; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.22 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/25.0.1364.152 Safari/537.22', '', 0, 0, 'N'); 
