INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (6266, 88895, '2013-08-16 17:53:53', '2013-08-16 09:53:53', 'Puddles in Lagos may be gaping pot holes so cars drive with care, making traffic so bad that homeward bound commutes can take 4 hours more than usual.  We initiated quick banter with a neighboring car with an open trunk during a dead standstill on a highway.  We leaned out the car windows into the thick air of the wet season to trade business cards.  We loosened our ties and noted with curiosity that we were bound in the same direction – and hotel. \r\n\r\nBeing born in Japan and raised in Taiwan exposed two economies and standards of living to me. This was a time when Japan had reached its zenith of modern development and Taiwan was rising as one of the Asian Tigers. Japan’s train timetables precise to the second are world renown. Taipei currently has world-class infrastructure and services despite decades of wage stagnation. Getting around the island is efficient, convenient, yet the air quality remains relatively high. I don’t know what I expected getting around in Lagos.  \r\n\r\nNow changed and downstairs in the hotel bar the Russians regale us about their gambling businesses across Africa and their Ghanaian friend is eager to impress with his web of connections. After a day of meetings and a missed lunch, the beer gets to my head and I feel my face redden. This place is swanky and I see big heads with wide swaggers. The Ghanaian provides surge protection – a protected industry. He says the regular brown outs are in the interest of privatized electrical production so they can pocket government subsidies. Either way, it’s good business for him and generator salesmen. Is that too absurd or did I mishear him? This is a country so well-endowed with crude oil yet refined oil must be re-imported and subsidized, with lines at gas stations when there are shortages. This is a city where I can pass business cards to Russians and Ghanaians on a highway but maybe it was the beer. \r\n\r\nMaybe you expect me to predict where the Nigerian economy is going – up – no, down – somewhere, who knows? There’re violent conflicts in the north, outdated infrastructure, and stigmas from the Yahoo boys and international fraud. Yet on the ground I meet smart, kind people eager to work and see a change in their country. My client tells me people are finally starting to come around to the idea of paying taxes and hope that the government will provide good infrastructure and services. Amazon doesn’t accept cards from Nigeria let alone deliver here, but novel solutions are popping up. Cash on delivery e-commerce circumvents the need for cards in a cash culture that mistrusts digital currency and companies like Jumia and Konga are reaping results. ', 'Thoughts on working in emerging markets like Lagos', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'thoughts-on-working-in-emerging-markets-like-lagos', '', '', '2013-10-09 10:40:30', '2013-10-09 02:40:30', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=6266', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
